1408","about 1386":"about 1386","Somerset, England":"Somerset, England","Sydenham, Somerset, England":"Sydenham, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Olivier.  Scandinavian Erik.","North German and Danish: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Boio</i>, possibly meaning ‘boy’ (see   Boy   1) or, alternatively, representing a variant of   Bothe  , with the regular Low German loss of the dental between vowels. This surname is also found in Norway and Sweden. Compare   Boie  .","English: variant of   Boy  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Boykin","meanings":["English: from a pet form of the Middle English personal name   Boye  .","History: Jarvis Boykin was one of the free planters who assented to the‘Fundamental Agreement’ of the New Haven Colony on June 4, 1639."]},{"name":"Beu","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Wolfgang.","North German:","variant of   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boysen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerd, Hans, Erwin, Hermann, Juergen, Lorenz, Siegfried.","North German, Danish, and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Emile, Fernand.","North German and Danish: variant of   Boye  .","Americanized form of French   Bois  ."]},{"name":"Bey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammed, Abdullah, Dawoud, Fatima, Jamaal, Rasheedah, Shakoor, Zaib, Aisha, Akil, Ameen, Aminah.","North German and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Beye</i> or <i>Baye</i>, vowel variants of   Boye  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Baj</b>: nickname or occupational name from Upper Sorbian <i>baj</i> ‘storyteller’. Compare   Bay  ."]},{"name":"Boje","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Goetz, Johannes.","German: variant of   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boyens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Georg.","North German and North Frisian: patronymic from the personal name   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans Peter, Heinz, Horst.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Boie</i>, which may be from ancient Germanic <i>Boio</i> (see   Boye   1 and 2) or an Old English <i>Boia</i>. The latter is common as a first element in English placenames, and is difficult to tell apart from the ordinary word <i>boy</i>, to which it may be related.","English: from Middle English <i>boy</i> ‘young man, servant’, also ‘knave’ or ‘rogue’. Compare   Ladd  ."]},{"name":"Boykins","meanings":["Americanized form of Dutch <b>Boeijkens</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Boye   with the diminutive element <i>-ken</i> and genitive <i>-s</i>. Compare the English cognate   Boykin   and North German   Boyken  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":69,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England